Part II - (Impact of Loan Features on Borrowers Rate)¶

by (Agbons Ekata-Inuaghata)¶

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset consisted of borrower APRs and attributes of 113,937 loans. The attributes utilised included original loan amount, borrower's Prosper rating, loan term, borrower's stated monthly income, as well as many other features such as employment status of borrowers, debt to income ratio, etc. I removed 352 data points from the analysis due to very large stated monthly income which seemed to be outliers also having missing borrower APR information.

Note that the above cells have been set as "Skip"-type slides. That means that when the notebook is rendered as http slides, those cells won't show up.

Borrower Rate and Original Loan Amount Distributions¶

The distribution of borrower rate looks bimodal. The highest point is at around 0.15 and the second peak is at around 0.32. No loans have interest rates up to 0.4

For original loan amount there are very large spikes in frequency are at 5k, 10k, 15k, 20k, 25k and a little spike at 35k. Most of the loans are multiples of 5k.

Year vs Borrower Rate¶

From our boxplot, we can observe that borrower rate fluctuated between 2005-2007, became steady from 2008-2010, and has been gradually decreasing since 2011 to 2014

Borrower rate vs Loan Original Amount and Available Bank Card Credit for all of the data.¶

  • The first plot shows that the borrower rate is negatively correlated with loan amount. The higher the loan amount, the lower the interest rate
  • The second plot shows that that the borrower rate is negatively correlated with the available bank card credit. The interest rate is negative at some point for bank card credits from 20000 to 60000 plus. Negative borrower interest rates encourage borrowers with higher bank card credits to borrow more

The Effect of Year on Relationship between Borrower Rate and Loan Amount¶

Aside from year 2005 which is an outlier because it has just 22 entries, Borrower rate seems to have a negative correlation with original loan amount across all other years. Another observation here is that there is a gradual increase in the loan amounts across the years

<Figure size 720x576 with 0 Axes>

Loan Status Effect on Relationship between Borrower Rate and Loan Amount¶

There seems to be a negative relationship across board here. A large category of defaulters seem to have taken smaller loans. I wonder why they are unable to pay their loans, despite their loan amounts being less than the borrowers who completed their loan payments. It could also mesn that the defaulters earn less and may not have very stable employment status
